According to the ANOVA table, we can conclude:

  1. The three factors hardwood concentration, cooking time and pressure all have relatively large \(F\)-statistic and \(p\)-values \(< \alpha = 0.05\), so all the main effects are statistically significant.

  2. Among all three two-way interaction terms, the interaction between hardwood concentration and cooking time (Hardwood\(\times\)Time) has \(F\)-statistic = 2.85 with \(p\)-value = 0.0843. The interaction between hardwood concentration and pressure (Hardwood\(\times\)Pressure) has \(F\)-statistic = 4.17 with \(p\)-value \(= 0.0146 < \alpha = 0.05\). The interaction between cooking time and pressure (Time\(\times\)Pressure) has \(F\)-statistic = 3.00 with \(p\)-value = 0.0750. Therefore, the interaction between hardwood concentration and pressure is statistically significant, and the other two two-way interaction terms are not significant but they have relatively small p-values.

  3. The three-way interaction term has \(F\)-statistic = 1.35 with \(p\)-value \(= 0.2903 > \alpha = 0.05\), so it is not significant.

Dropping the 3-way interaction gives us the following model:

## drop non-significant term
drop1(fit1) ## we should drop 3-way interaction

b) Model diagnostics

plot(fit1, which = c(1, 2))

# residual plot for each factor
data %>% select(-Strength) %>%
  mutate(res = fit1$residuals) %>%
  melt(., id.vars = c("res")) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = value, y = res)) +
  geom_point(shape = 1, color = "blue") +
  geom_hline(aes(yintercept = 0)) +
  facet_wrap(~variable, nrow = 3, scale = "free_x") +
  labs(x = "", y = "Residual", title = "Plot of resisuals vs. 3 factors")

The above five plots of residuals are used to check basic assumptions:

  1. In the QQ plot, the residuals slightly departure from the straight line in the middle region and shows a S-shape, which indicates that the normality assumption might be violated (but might not be a big problem since the departure is tiny).

  2. According to the plot of residuals vs. predicted values, there is no obvious pattern: residuals are randomly distributed and form a roughly parallel band around the horizontal line about 0. According to the plot of residuals vs. hardwood concentration (1st in the panel), there is no obvious pattern: residuals are randomly distributed over types of hardwood and form a roughly parallel band around the horizontal line about 0. Similar results are obtained from the plot of residuals vs. cooking time (2nd in the panel) and vs. pressure (3rd in the panel). Therefore, the assumption of constant variance is satisfied. Besides, all plots show no obvious outliers.

Comment about model’s adequacy:

sst = sum((data$Strength - mean(data$Strength))^2)
dft = nrow(data) - 1

sse = sum(fit1$residuals^2)
dfe = 18
mse = sse/dfe

ssr = sst - sse
dfr = dft - dfe
msr = ssr/dfr

fstats = msr/mse
pval = 1 - pf(q = fstats, df1 = dfr, df2 = dfe)
rsq = ssr/sst

We can compute \(\text{SST}= \sum_{i = 1}^n(y_i - \bar{y})^2 = 66.3089\), \(\text{SSE}= 6.58\), and \(\text{SSR}= \text{SST}- \text{SSE}= 59.7289\). The ANOVA table for the overall model is summarized as follows:

SS DF MS F p
Model 17 3.5135 9.6113 0
Error 18 0.3656
Total 35
  1. For the model, we get \(F\)-statistic = 9.61 with \(p\)-value \(< 0.0001 < \alpha = 0.05\), so we conclude that the model is significant and useful.
  2. \(R^2 = \frac{\text{SSR}}{SST} = 0.9008\). This indicates that about 90.08% of the variation in the response can be explained by the model, which is a good fit.

To maximize the strength of paper, we should operate the process under the set of conditions: the percentage of hardwood concentration is 2, the cooking time of the pulp is 4.0 hours, and the vat pressure is 650.

We can also use Tukey’s method for pairwise comparisons for all treatment combinations. The treatment combination (hardwood = 2, time = 4 and pressure = 650) has the largest estimate.
